## Errors & Mistakes
- First test run of tests/flow/test_evaluation_imperative.py + test_client_trace.py
  showed "5 failed" plus a flood of "Error during cleanup of EvaluationLogger"
  atexit tracebacks. The atexit noise is unrelated teardown logging. The 5
  failures (test_evaluation_invalid_model_name_fixable/not_fixable) are
  PRE-EXISTING ON MASTER: I git-stashed my changes (incl. untracked op_lifecycle.py
  via `git stash push -u`) and confirmed the identical 5 failures on clean master.
  Root cause: EvaluationLogger.__init__ calls require_weave_client() at
  eval_imperative.py:792 BEFORE validating the model name, and those parametrized
  tests run without an initialized client. Nothing to do with this refactor.
- ruff format wanted to reflow op.py (my multi-line call args). op.py is NOT in the
  serialization-sensitive ruff-format exclusion list (those are Content/Audio/
  update_costs), so formatting was safe. Verified the diff only touched my edits.

## Dead Ends
- Considered collapsing the 4 paths into 2 (_run_func/_run_gen with is_async) but
  the sync/async control flow (await points, StopIteration vs StopAsyncIteration,
  sync vs async generator wrappers) genuinely differs; merging would be riskier
  than the duplication it removes. Kept 4 entry points, shared only the lifecycle.
- Considered tightening getattr(op, "_on_finish_post_processor", None) to direct
  attribute access. Deferred to keep this a pure structural refactor (the OpState
  PR is the right place). Preserved getattr semantics exactly.

## Hints for Future Agents
- CallFinisher.has_finished is PUBLIC on purpose: the generator paths read it to
  decide whether to also finish on an error path (mirrors the old nonlocal flag).
- _call_sync_gen's skip check is `should_skip_tracing_for_op(op)` ONLY, while
  _call_sync_func also checks is_tracing_setting_disabled(). This asymmetry is
  pre-existing and intentional-looking; it was NOT changed. Do not "fix" it here.
- The empty_sync_gen/empty_async_gen fallbacks rely on finish.has_finished being
  False when require_explicit_finish=True (CallFinisher returns before setting the
  flag), so they re-raise. This matches the old closure behavior.

